-if realm.adjective == "affective"
  =render "affect"

%p The #{realm.adjective} realm runs on #{realm.energy}.
%p You use #{realm.energy} in order to #{realm.act} and #{realm.achieve_goals}. The more you #{realm.act}, the more #{realm.energy} you need, whether or not you are trying to #{realm.achieve} #{realm.anything}. The harder #{realm.goals} are to #{realm.achieve}, the more #{realm.strength} you will develop while #{realm.achieve.ing} #{realm.them_there}. The more #{realm.strength} you have, the more #{realm.energy} you need to fuel #{realm.it_them}. If you don’t continually use and fuel your #{realm.strength} #{realm.it_they} will atrophy.
%p In order to get #{realm.energy} you need to #{realm.get_resources}. It is difficult to #{realm.get_resources} you cannot #{realm.notice} or that #{realm.appear} bad. Most #{realm.resources} are a combination of #{realm.strengtheners} and #{realm.energizers}. #{realm.resources.capitalize} that are mostly #{realm.energizers} are easier to #{realm.get} and #{realm.process} than those that are primarily #{realm.strengtheners} but #{realm.strengtheners} #{realm.is_are} essential if you want to develop #{realm.strength}. If you #{realm.get} more #{realm.strengtheners} than you need, you won’t spontaneously build more #{realm.strength}, but if you #{realm.get} more #{realm.energizers} than you need, the excess #{realm.energy} will be stored as #{realm.reserves} for later use.
